made with balloons, but these are in no sense

00:14:23.510 --> 00:14:24.880
true flying machines."

00:14:24.880 --> 00:14:28.910
"Everyone who attempted a solution to the
question by machines heavier than the air,

00:14:28.910 --> 00:14:33.180
was looked upon in very much the same light
as a man who now attempts to construct a perpetual

00:14:33.180 --> 00:14:34.300
motion machine."

00:14:34.300 --> 00:14:40.930
"Up to within a few years, nearly all experiments
in aerial navigation by flying machines have

00:14:40.930 --> 00:14:44.980
been made by men not versed in science, and
who, for the most part, have been ignorant

00:14:44.980 --> 00:14:49.130
of the most rudimentary laws of dynamics.
It's only quite recently that scientific engineers

00:14:49.130 --> 00:14:53.590
have taken up the question and removed it
from the hands of charlatans and mountebanks."

00:14:53.590 --> 00:14:55.680
Mountebanks is a word I'd like to bring back.

00:14:55.680 --> 00:14:59.990
"A few years ago, many engineers would not
have dared to face the ridicule, which they

00:14:59.990 --> 00:15:03.970
would be liable to receive if they had asserted
that it be possible to make a machine that

00:15:03.970 --> 00:15:06.410
would lift itself by mechanical means into
the air."

00:15:06.410 --> 00:15:10.970
"However, thanks to the admirable work of
Professor Langley, Professor Thurston, Mister

00:15:10.970 --> 00:15:15.290
Chanute and others, one may now express his
opinion freely on the subject and speculate

00:15:15.290 --> 00:15:19.100
as to the possibilities of making flying machines,
without being relegated to the realm of cranks

00:15:19.100 --> 00:15:20.100
and fanatics."

00:15:20.100 --> 00:15:25.820
So, this decade of the 1890s was when the
science of powered flight was really starting

00:15:25.820 --> 00:15:34.670
to come into real, under scientific scrutiny.
He, Hiram Maxim, was such an inventor and

00:15:34.670 --> 00:15:38.530
so wealthy by this point, that he could build
giant machines.

00:15:38.530 --> 00:15:43.490
And he had a hanger out there near London
where he was building his experiments and

00:15:43.490 --> 00:15:48.190
he built multiple propellers to see which
would work the most efficiently in the air.

00:15:48.190 --> 00:15:56.080
And he is really dedicated to solving this
problem. This is a latter-day artist's representation

00:15:56.080 --> 00:16:02.200
of what happened on his most successful, and
last, flight.

00:16:02.200 --> 00:16:05.800
The machine--. And the reason he used the
steam boiler was not because he was an idiot,

00:16:05.800 --> 00:16:12.110
but because at the time it was the most efficient
per pound, horsepower per pound. And he had

00:16:12.110 --> 00:16:17.260
a rail that he ran that ship on. And he had
another rail balanced above it because he

00:16:17.260 --> 00:16:20.940
didn’t' want the thing to go too high and
to actually collapse.

00:16:20.940 --> 00:16:25.820
He just wanted to learn if he could control
it for that six inches. So, the thing went

00:16:25.820 --> 00:16:31.110
down the rail and it lifted off, and it hit
that top rail. And it broke the top rail because

00:16:31.110 --> 00:16:38.310
it had this great up, burst of lift. And it
actually snapped the track and it fell over

00:16:38.310 --> 00:16:39.310
and it was destroyed.

00:16:39.310 --> 00:16:40.870
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #3: So, he made it.

00:16:40.870 --> 00:16:45.550
&gt;&gt;David Malki: So he made it. That's the thing.
He made it horribly uncontrollably, but he

00:16:45.550 --> 00:16:47.660
made it. This is what he says about the accident.

00:16:47.660 --> 00:16:48.660
[reads from article]

00:16:48.660 --> 00:16:53.140
"I found myself floating in the air with the
feeling of being in a boat, but unfortunately,

00:16:53.140 --> 00:16:57.640
a piece of the broken plank struck one of
the screws, the propellers, and smashed it.

00:16:57.640 --> 00:17:01.232
I instantly shut off steam and the machine
came to a state of rest on the earth, the

00:17:01.232 --> 00:17:05.120
wheels cutting deeply into the ground and
leaving no track, thus showing that they had

00:17:05.120 --> 00:17:08.480
sunk down vertically and had not run along
the ground before settling.

00:17:08.480 --> 00:17:12.339
“This was the first time in the history
of the world that a flying machine actually

00:17:12.339 --> 00:17:15.140
lifted itself and a man into the air."

00:17:15.140 --> 00:17:20.620
1893. Now, he goes on to talk about, "The
machine was practically the same as the Farman

00:17:20.620 --> 00:17:24.449
machine" and so on. "If I had a larger field,"
the quantity of water was too much.

00:17:24.449 --> 00:17:28.950
Here are all the things I can fix. "Shortly
after this accident, I received notice from

00:17:28.950 --> 00:17:33.539
the landlord that the property had been sold
to the London County Council for the purpose

00:17:33.539 --> 00:17:38.800
of erecting a very large imbecile asylum.
It appears that I had prepared the ground,

00:17:38.800 --> 00:17:42.570
so all that was necessary was to erect the
buildings."

00:17:42.570 --> 00:17:43.570
[laughter]

00:17:43.570 --> 00:17:50.710
He never did build his flying machine. And
he turned his attentions elsewhere. But he

00:17:50.710 --> 00:17:55.879
was so dedicated to bring scientific rigor
to this field, that he contributed immeasurably

00:17:55.879 --> 00:18:01.710
to the field of the science of aeronautics.
He knows how he disparaged ballooning.

00:18:01.710 --> 00:18:06.230
That's because they were a bunch of idiots
out there with balloons at the time. In his

00:18:06.230 --> 00:18:10.200
very excellent report recently made on the
progress of aeronautics to the British Aeronautical

00:18:10.200 --> 00:18:15.559
Society, Mr. Francis W. Berry says, "It is
singular that no one has taken advantage of

00:18:15.559 --> 00:18:21.039
an ascertained fact to put the balloon to
more pleasurable, has more prolonged use than

00:18:21.039 --> 00:18:22.360
has hitherto been attempted."

00:18:22.360 --> 00:18:26.529
"After interesting how a boat may be caused
travel by the current of the stream by simply

00:18:26.529 --> 00:18:31.009
using the pole to push clear of the banks,"
he adds, "there is every probability that

00:18:31.009 --> 00:18:36.269
with a balloon so balanced, a push with a
long pole would sent it spinning for 50 feet

00:18:36.269 --> 00:18:40.700
or more, and one might traverse a few hundred
yards before it neared the earth, and it required

00:18:40.700 --> 00:18:41.700
another push."

00:18:41.700 --> 00:18:46.149
So, they're talking about taking a balloon,
floating it so much so that it's balanced

00:18:46.149 --> 00:18:51.799
with the lift versus the weight, just hovering
in the air. Then you can just be a gondola,

00:18:51.799 --> 00:18:54.710
just pull yourself around. Why not, right?

00:18:54.710 --> 00:18:55.710
[laughter]

00:18:55.710 --> 00:19:02.830
You can drive a boat with it. "Shortly before
undertaking ascension in which he lost his

00:19:02.830 --> 00:19:03.830
life,--

00:19:03.830 --> 00:19:04.830
[laughter]

00:19:04.830 --> 00:19:09.129
Donaldson, the well-known aeronaut described
to us his experience in just such balloon

00:19:09.129 --> 00:19:14.610
sailing." Who is Mr. Donaldson? Mr. Donaldson
is Washington Harrison Donaldson. And this

00:19:14.610 --> 00:19:19.720
guy was amazing. This guy was the guy you
think of when you think "crazy man."

00:19:19.720 --> 00:19:20.720
[laughter]

00:19:20.720 --> 00:19:26.350
From the 1800s, who goes around doing nonsense.
He was a circus performer who decided that

00:19:26.350 --> 00:19:28.490
circuses were too sedate for him.

00:19:28.490 --> 00:19:29.490
[laughter]

00:19:29.490 --> 00:19:34.710
So, what he wanted to do was get into ballooning
and do circus acts from a balloon. So, what

00:19:34.710 --> 00:19:40.740
he would do was go up in a balloon, cut the
basket free, and then be on a trapeze, dangling

00:19:40.740 --> 00:19:46.009
from the balloon. And then drift across farmlands
doing trapeze acts. And people would look

00:19:46.009 --> 00:19:48.300
up and go, "What the hell is that?"

00:19:48.300 --> 00:19:49.300
[laughter]

00:19:49.300 --> 00:19:54.149
Then they would follow him and when he came
down, I guess they would give him money. I'm

00:19:54.149 --> 00:19:55.149
not sure.

00:19:55.149 --> 00:19:56.149
[laughter]

00:19:56.149 --> 00:19:59.850
P.T. Barnum did, eventually, like--. He got
his money from people like Barnum and giant

00:19:59.850 --> 00:20:03.100
newspapers who were like "Put our logo on
your next balloon." And he's like, "Yes, OK.

00:20:03.100 --> 00:20:04.100
No problem."

00:20:04.100 --> 00:20:10.860
But he was a real pioneer in ballooning. And
he had to figure out at every step, when someone

00:20:10.860 --> 00:20:15.130
like Barnum came and said, "I wanna build
a balloon twice as big as anything else."

00:20:15.130 --> 00:20:18.470
Donaldson said, "No problem. I can fly it."
And he had no idea how to fly it.

00:20:18.470 --> 00:20:19.470
[laughter]

00:20:19.470 --> 00:20:23.919
He just had to invent it, but there were mishaps
along the way. This was his first flight.

00:20:23.919 --> 00:20:27.860
He got the balance wrong and he had to throw
out his hat, coat, and boots to make the thing

00:20:27.860 --> 00:20:31.520
light enough to take off. This was a later
flight.

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:32.580
[laughter]

00:20:32.580 --> 00:20:37.280
That's Donaldson at the bottom. And that's
a man from the press in the middle. And up

00:20:37.280 --> 00:20:43.480
there is, I think, a different reporter. And
what happened was a storm kicked up and Donaldson

00:20:43.480 --> 00:20:47.940
said, "We gotta bail out. Everyone get by
the basket and hang on and then we'll all

00:20:47.940 --> 00:20:48.980
jump at the same time.

00:20:48.980 --> 00:20:54.289
Well, the guy--. One of the guys didn't hear
him properly. And so, Donaldson and this other

00:20:54.289 --> 00:21:00.640
guy, Ford, they're dangling and they jump
out and the balloon shoots upward because

00:21:00.640 --> 00:21:04.629
now it's so much lighter. And this guy is
stuck in the basket. He goes another two miles

00:21:04.629 --> 00:21:11.230
and eventually has to jump out into a tree.
And this was par for the course.

00:21:11.230 --> 00:21:12.230
[laughter]

00:21:12.230 --> 00:21:17.110
So, this is from--. From this perspective,
like that's who this guy is when he says,

00:21:17.110 --> 00:21:22.120
"Mr. Donaldson stated as his belief that if
ever the time came when people would step

00:21:22.120 --> 00:21:26.309
into balloons as readily as they now do into
railroad cars, the airship would not sail

00:21:26.309 --> 00:21:29.570
above the clouds, but would skim close along
the surface of the ground."

00:21:29.570 --> 00:21:32.519
You didn't want to get too high 'cause who
knows what would happen, right? He doesn't

00:21:32.519 --> 00:21:37.140
have a great track record with this thing.
He's like, "You can totally fly a balloon,

00:21:37.140 --> 00:21:38.990
but just, let's keep it low."

00:21:38.990 --> 00:21:39.990
[laughter]

00:21:39.990 --> 00:21:43.309
"He gave many reasons for this view, notably
increased safety and economies, as balloons

00:21:43.309 --> 00:21:47.450
could be made much smaller as they would not
require a large amount gas to keep them afloat,

00:21:47.450 --> 00:21:50.919
and there is little difficulty in stopping
to replenish the supply when exhausted.

00:21:50.919 --> 00:21:55.399
“He had found no trouble in balancing the
balloon four feet above the ground, and keeping

00:21:55.399 --> 00:21:56.720
it accurately at that height for hours."

00:21:56.720 --> 00:21:59.740
He's sitting there for hours, four feet above
the ground.

00:21:59.740 --> 00:22:05.179
"He told us further that he frequently travelled
along country roads in this way during calm

00:22:05.179 --> 00:22:09.789
weather, using a pole to push himself along
when there was no wind, or to guide himself

00:22:09.789 --> 00:22:11.799
when being wafted by a breeze."

00:22:11.799 --> 00:22:16.529
This is when you start to realize, I don't
know if he actually did this, but there's

00:22:16.529 --> 00:22:20.409
value in newspaper's thinking you did that
because it makes you awesome in their mind.

00:22:20.409 --> 00:22:24.389
They're like, "Donaldson? He'll do anything.
He's polling a balloon around."

00:22:24.389 --> 00:22:25.389
[laughter]

00:22:25.389 --> 00:22:28.789
Yet, he didn't actually have to do it to get
the article written about him. But maybe he

00:22:28.789 --> 00:22:29.789
did.

00:22:29.789 --> 00:22:34.269
"As an instance of how exactly a balloon can
be balanced, he stated that while thus sailing

00:22:34.269 --> 00:22:38.920
over a road, he carelessly dropped overboard
about a quarter of a loaf of bread, whereupon

00:22:38.920 --> 00:22:41.730
the airship sprang aloft a hundred feet or
more."

00:22:41.730 --> 00:22:47.039
"We asked him how he avoided wagons and other
similar obstacles in his path without discharging

00:22:47.039 --> 00:22:51.659
balance and so losing equilibrium. 'Jump over
them,' was his answer. 'A good strong push

00:22:51.659 --> 00:22:56.273
downwards on my guiding pole has sent me flying
over many a tree, in which I had thought I

00:22:56.273 --> 00:22:57.730
was sure to be entangled.'"

00:22:57.730 --> 00:23:03.999
"This flee-like mode of progression was a
favorite mode he had of astonishing Arestics."

00:23:03.999 --> 00:23:07.720
That's another phrase I wanna bring back.
Astonishing Arestics. So, here's--. Let's

00:23:07.720 --> 00:23:13.539
go back to Maxim for just a second. "Experiments
of this character" meaning aeronautical experiments

00:23:13.539 --> 00:23:17.740
in general, "unless conducted with great care
are exceedingly dangerous.

00:23:17.740 --> 00:23:22.499
"No make-shift or imperfect apparatus should
be employed, but the experimenter should have

00:23:22.499 --> 00:23:27.480
the advantage of the most perfect appliances
and apparatus that modern civilization can

00:23:27.480 --> 00:23:31.460
afford. The necessary plan for conducting
experiments in a proper and safe manner is

00:23:31.460 --> 00:23:34.039
unfortunately much more expensive than the
machine itself."

00:23:34.039 --> 00:23:38.210
"If I find that my experiments require more
money than I have in my disposal, I feel sure

00:23:38.210 --> 00:23:43.289
that some future experimenters are more fortunate
will commence where I leave off and so on."

00:23:43.289 --> 00:23:49.400
This guy was a consummate scientist to be
looked up to by everyone in the sciences.

00:23:49.400 --> 00:23:58.100
Meanwhile, Donaldson. The 48th ascension and
he made 130 something before he did not come

00:23:58.100 --> 00:24:03.230
back from one, was made on May 15th, 1874.
"The villagers gathered around him like the

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:06.620
natives did around Columbus, and watched every
movement he made.

00:24:06.620 --> 00:24:10.309
"After taking a sufficient number of stores,
he took his departure amid the cheers and

00:24:10.309 --> 00:24:15.379
hurrahs of the crowd. During this trip he
engaged in the delightful sport of trailing

00:24:15.379 --> 00:24:19.760
the drag-rope." This is the rope that hangs
from the balloon so people can grab it and

00:24:19.760 --> 00:24:20.899
pull it back down to earth.

00:24:20.899 --> 00:24:24.639
"Bushes would be bent over, and rail fences
jerked open with a degree of speed not common

00:24:24.639 --> 00:24:27.940
for the farmers." So, this balloon is being
pushed by the wind. And there's an anchor

00:24:27.940 --> 00:24:33.399
on this thing and it's just tearing through
everything in its path. "Chickens scampered

00:24:33.399 --> 00:24:36.080
for their lives, and sheep would run in every
direction."

00:24:36.080 --> 00:24:40.830
"As he was passing along he chanced to go
over a yard where a man and a woman were engaged

00:24:40.830 --> 00:24:45.770
in making apple butter. Donaldson has an eye
for business, and concluded he would thicken

00:24:45.770 --> 00:24:50.110
the apple butter for them, and at the proper
time he poured a lot of sand out of a bag

00:24:50.110 --> 00:24:52.909
that went direct into the kettle of apple
butter."

00:24:52.909 --> 00:24:57.640
"The woman looked up and saw, just then Donaldson
gave a few terrible blasts on his bugle and

00:24:57.640 --> 00:24:59.119
made some remarks about 'Gabriel and the judgment.'"

00:24:59.119 --> 00:25:00.119
[laughter]

00:25:00.119 --> 00:25:04.070
This was the other thing he liked to do. He
carried a bugle aloft. Another flight, in

00:25:04.070 --> 00:25:08.720
which he was flying at night, he started blowing
on the trumpet and saying, "Gabriel is here."

00:25:08.720 --> 00:25:13.070
And all the lights would go off in all the
houses beneath as people start to pray.

00:25:13.070 --> 00:25:18.090
"The woman took a tantrum, fell down, and
rolled over two or three times and started

00:25:18.090 --> 00:25:22.519
for the house on 'all fours,' after the broom
and butcher knife. The man, after getting

00:25:22.519 --> 00:25:26.320
the sand out of his face and mouth sufficiently
to see the cause of all the trouble, drew

00:25:26.320 --> 00:25:30.169
back the ladle, and with a clenched fist,
he threatened to demolish the 'man and the

00:25:30.169 --> 00:25:31.169
balloon.'"

00:25:31.169 --> 00:25:36.100
"Donaldson was wafted out of sight to the
tune of that man's 'chin music' at the rate

00:25:36.100 --> 00:25:40.619
of about 'two-forty on the pike.' The trailing
and sailing were continued for some time,

00:25:40.619 --> 00:25:44.200
and by means of variable currents he traveled
over a big portion of Southern and Central

00:25:44.200 --> 00:25:45.200
New York."

00:25:45.200 --> 00:25:48.919
"After a three hours' ride he landed at Half
Way Station, between Auburn and Syracuse,

00:25:48.919 --> 00:25:53.610
at least one hundred miles from point of starting
direct line. The gas was let out, and the

00:25:53.610 --> 00:25:57.470
balloon shipped to Ithaca by way of Geneva.
The balloon had to remain at the depot at

00:25:57.470 --> 00:26:00.920
Geneva all night, but as that building was
consumed by fire on the same night the balloon

00:26:00.920 --> 00:26:01.920
was burned up."

00:26:01.920 --> 00:26:02.920
[laughter]

00:26:02.920 --> 00:26:07.049
This happened all the time. So, you could
never tell what was gonna happen, if you had

00:26:07.049 --> 00:26:10.419
a delightful day of ruining apple butter,
your balloon could be consumed by a fire the

00:26:10.419 --> 00:26:16.909
same night. Such was the life of an adventurer
in the 1800s. Nothing was taken for granted.

00:26:16.909 --> 00:26:22.350
But everyone was consumed with the spirit
of adventure. And here is a humorous column

00:26:22.350 --> 00:26:28.240
from Scientific American and that some of
you may relate to. "How the inventor plagues

00:26:28.240 --> 00:26:29.970
his poor wife."

00:26:29.970 --> 00:26:34.279
"A facetious chap connected with one of our
daily newspapers gives the following amusing

00:26:34.279 --> 00:26:38.539
burlesque on the trials of an inventor’s
wife: 'It is all very well to talk about working

00:26:38.539 --> 00:26:41.890
for the heathen,' said one, as the ladies
put up their sewing, 'but I’d like to have

00:26:41.890 --> 00:26:43.909
someone tell me what I am to do with my husband.'"

00:26:43.909 --> 00:26:47.919
"'What is the matter with him?' asked a sympathetic
old lady. 'William is a good man,' continued

00:26:47.919 --> 00:26:53.889
the first, waving her glasses in an argumentative
way, 'but William will invent. He goes inventing

00:26:53.889 --> 00:26:56.549
round from morning till night, and I have
no peace or comfort."

00:26:56.549 --> 00:27:01.460
"I didn’t object when he invented a fire
escape, but I did remonstrate when he wanted

00:27:01.460 --> 00:27:05.090
me to crawl out of the window one night last
winter to see how it worked. Then he originated

00:27:05.090 --> 00:27:08.539
a lock for the door that wouldn’t open from
midnight until morning to keep burglars out."

00:27:08.539 --> 00:27:13.100
"The first time he tried it he caught his
coat-tail in it, and I had to walk around

00:27:13.100 --> 00:27:16.679
him with a pan of hot coals all night to keep
him from freezing.' 'Well, why didn’t he

00:27:16.679 --> 00:27:20.000
take his coat off?' 'Well, I wanted him to,
but he stood around till the thing opened

00:27:20.000 --> 00:27:23.139
itself, trying to invent some way of unfastening
it."

00:27:23.139 --> 00:27:27.999
"That’s William’s trouble. He will invent.
A little while ago he got up a cabinet bedstead

00:27:27.999 --> 00:27:32.690
that would shut and open without handling.
It went by clockwork. William got into it,

00:27:32.690 --> 00:27:36.360
and up it went. Bless your heart, he stayed
in there from Saturday afternoon till Sunday

00:27:36.360 --> 00:27:40.710
night, when it flew open and disclosed William
with the plans and specifications of a patent

00:27:40.710 --> 00:27:43.509
washbowl that would tip over just when it
got so full."

00:27:43.509 --> 00:27:47.850
"The result was that I lost all my rings and
a breastpin down the wastepipe. Then he got

00:27:47.850 --> 00:27:51.619
up a crutch for a man that could also be used
as an opera-glass. Whenever the man leaned

00:27:51.619 --> 00:27:55.530
on it up it went, and when he put it to his
eye to find William, it flew out into a crutch

00:27:55.530 --> 00:27:57.809
and almost broke the top of his head off."

00:27:57.809 --> 00:28:01.279
"Once he invented a rope ladder to be worn
as a guard chain and lengthened out with a

00:28:01.279 --> 00:28:04.690
spring. He put it around his neck, but the
spring got loose and turned it into a ladder

00:28:04.690 --> 00:28:09.161
and almost choked him to death. Then he invented
a patent boot heel to crack nuts with, but

00:28:09.161 --> 00:28:12.110
he mashed his thumb with it and gave it up."

00:28:12.110 --> 00:28:17.249
"Why, he has a washtub full of inventions.
One of them is a prayer book that always opens

00:28:17.249 --> 00:28:21.269
at the right place. We tried it one morning
at church, but the wheels and springs made

00:28:21.269 --> 00:28:25.039
such a noise that the sexton took William
by the collar and told him to leave his fire

00:28:25.039 --> 00:28:27.470
engines at home when he came to worship."

00:28:27.470 --> 00:28:30.110
"The other day I saw him going up the street
with a model of a grain elevator sticking

00:28:30.110 --> 00:28:33.860
out of his hip pocket, and he is fixing up
an improved shot-tower in our bedroom."

00:28:33.860 --> 00:28:39.739
When I read this, it made me think there's
something about human nature that doesn't

00:28:39.739 --> 00:28:41.520
change over time.

00:28:41.520 --> 00:28:42.520
[laughter]

00:28:42.520 --> 00:28:48.779
And here's another wonderful example of that.
This is Nature. This is the evidence that

00:28:48.779 --> 00:28:54.481
not everybody is as excited about progress.
If you've never heard, I'm sure you have,

00:28:54.481 --> 00:29:01.090
the idea that the kids today, the technological
advances we have are--.

00:29:01.090 --> 00:29:06.400
We're losing something important about our
humanity. My thesis is that we always felt

00:29:06.400 --> 00:29:12.749
that way. Always. Even back when, a hundred
years ago, when we feel like things may have

00:29:12.749 --> 00:29:13.919
been simpler.

00:29:13.919 --> 00:29:15.080
[reads article]

00:29:15.080 --> 00:29:19.970
"Now, new penalties and distresses persistently
and inexorably follow each new invention,

00:29:19.970 --> 00:29:25.029
and that which man believes to be for his
melioration inevitably bears a satellite of

00:29:25.029 --> 00:29:26.049
evil in its train."

00:29:26.049 --> 00:29:30.270
"Fresh calamities and new diseases not only
come to view, but they are discovered to be

00:29:30.270 --> 00:29:34.909
actually produced by the novel appliances
which have been regarded as benefits and wonderful

00:29:34.909 --> 00:29:39.990
improvements. Household conveniences beget
unexpected annoyances, rapid locomotion involves

00:29:39.990 --> 00:29:45.639
fatalities, and mechanical contrivances to
reduce labor impoverish multitudes while they

00:29:45.639 --> 00:29:46.639
benefit the few."

00:29:46.639 --> 00:29:51.480
"Indeed, it may be stated as a postulate,
on general principles, that the ratio of evil

00:29:51.480 --> 00:29:56.779
is a hundred to one of good accomplished by
man’s inventions. But man’s progressive

00:29:56.779 --> 00:30:00.499
works are not only destroying himself, but
they are hastening the destruction of the

00:30:00.499 --> 00:30:04.230
Earth, in whose ultimate fate mankind is commonly
involved."

00:30:04.230 --> 00:30:08.600
"It may well be questioned whether, in view
of the startling and unforeseen consequences

00:30:08.600 --> 00:30:13.000
of scientific success which have changed the
aspect and economy of the entire globe within

00:30:13.000 --> 00:30:19.429
the last fifty years, we have not overstepped
the moral bounds of science by perverting

00:30:19.429 --> 00:30:23.700
the knowledge which Man came into possession
of surreptitiously when he ate of the 'forbidden

00:30:23.700 --> 00:30:24.700
fruit.'"

00:30:24.700 --> 00:30:30.020
"When Benjamin Franklin first called down
the lightning from the sky he was accursed

00:30:30.020 --> 00:30:36.460
by the superstitious or reverential with 'tempting
the Almighty.' Now we handle the subtile element,

00:30:36.460 --> 00:30:41.700
electricity, as if it were inert matter, and
we impress it into our nurseries as a toy

00:30:41.700 --> 00:30:42.700
for the children!"

00:30:42.700 --> 00:30:48.669
"We tap the bowels of the earth and subject
to our domestic use the vapors. We experiment

00:30:48.669 --> 00:30:53.320
with the volcano and the geyser, the mysterious
medicine spring and the poisoned valley. We

00:30:53.320 --> 00:30:57.190
toy with the weirdest phenomena of Nature
as if they were familiar spirits."

00:30:57.190 --> 00:31:03.149
"We have builded a Tower of Babel at Paris,
and we have phonographed the breath of life

00:31:03.149 --> 00:31:07.190
so that the dead may speak years after they
have departed from the earth." And not like

00:31:07.190 --> 00:31:12.750
the glossograph. "For years we have been attempting
to make water burn" no idea what he means

00:31:12.750 --> 00:31:17.749
there, "perverting the Divine economy to the
economy of Man, and reversing the purposes

00:31:17.749 --> 00:31:18.779
of the Creator."

00:31:18.779 --> 00:31:22.399
"As soon as ever the effort is crowned with
success, the destruction of the world is no

00:31:22.399 --> 00:31:27.799
longer a question of centuries, but of years.
At present our most dangerous pet is electricity:

00:31:27.799 --> 00:31:30.340
in the telegraph, the street lamp and the
telephone."

00:31:30.340 --> 00:31:34.550
"We have introduced electric power into our
simplest domestic industries, and we have

00:31:34.550 --> 00:31:40.020
woven this most subtle of agents, once active
only in the sublimes manifestations of Omnipotence,

00:31:40.020 --> 00:31:44.899
like a web about our dwellings, and filled
our atmosphere with the filaments of death."

00:31:44.899 --> 00:31:49.159
"It is urged that electric lighting is not
essential to the public comfort. It is not

00:31:49.159 --> 00:31:55.109
a necessity but a luxury. By abolishing it
we reduce our danger appreciably. The telegraph

00:31:55.109 --> 00:31:59.970
is essential to rapid intercommunication in
this age, and will be retained, but its operation

00:31:59.970 --> 00:32:01.390
must be subjected to proper safeguards."

00:32:01.390 --> 00:32:07.630
"The telephone is the most dangerous of all
because it enters into every dwelling. Its

00:32:07.630 --> 00:32:11.989
interminable network of wires is a perpetual
menace to life and property. In its best performance

00:32:11.989 --> 00:32:19.269
it is only a convenience. It was never a necessity.
In a multitude of cities its service is unsatisfactory

00:32:19.269 --> 00:32:20.669
and is being dispensed with."

00:32:20.669 --> 00:32:26.249
Some things do not change. "Already the conservative
public has taken the alarm, and it has become

00:32:26.249 --> 00:32:31.080
our urgent duty, in the interest of personal
safety, think of the children, to clip the

00:32:31.080 --> 00:32:34.279
pinions of the winged messenger and draw its
claws."

00:32:34.279 --> 00:32:38.549
"Measures are in order to undo the mischief
as rapidly as possible and to get back to

00:32:38.549 --> 00:32:40.960
as safe a condition as we were before."

00:32:40.960 --> 00:32:49.379
So, there's always two sides to everything.
And I also found people who objected to the

00:32:49.379 --> 00:32:53.850
invention of the printing press and the notion
of writing, itself.

00:32:53.850 --> 00:32:54.850
[laughter]

00:32:54.850 --> 00:32:59.730
I think what we do as humans is fear change,
not the technology in particular, but simply

00:32:59.730 --> 00:33:05.720
things that are different. This is a comic
from Punchinello Magazine, which is the New

00:33:05.720 --> 00:33:09.750
York version of the great London satirical
Punch.

00:33:09.750 --> 00:33:14.659
And we've got a lecture there giving a talk.
Maybe the talk we just heard. The lady there,

00:33:14.659 --> 00:33:20.299
with the ear trumpet. Fellow there in the
back kinda snoozing. And here's a guy trying

00:33:20.299 --> 00:33:23.867
to take notes up in the front. The lecturer
says, "There is a cumulative approximativeness,

00:33:23.867 --> 00:33:26.870
so to speak, a period when the recalcitrant
corpuscles begins to--."

00:33:26.870 --> 00:33:30.989
And the stenographer is thinking, “Confound
the fellow! I knew he’d break my pencil

00:33:30.989 --> 00:33:36.029
with his infernal jaw-smashers!” Jaw-smashers
I would like to bring back.

00:33:36.029 --> 00:33:37.029
[laughter]

00:33:37.029 --> 00:33:44.940
I'm taking notes. And the humor of this age
is really, really interesting to me as well

00:33:44.940 --> 00:33:51.429
because it speaks to so much of the national
character, but also a sensibility of how to

00:33:51.429 --> 00:33:53.840
tell stories that has really changed over
time.

00:33:53.840 --> 00:33:59.129
For example, here's a little joke that was
published in Harper's. "I was perambulating

00:33:59.129 --> 00:34:03.470
the piazza of the blank Hotel, in company
with the daughter of the landlord. She had

00:34:03.470 --> 00:34:07.340
been recounting to me all her father's little
successes and reverses in life ever since

00:34:07.340 --> 00:34:12.020
he had adopted the profession of a Boniface,
and among the latter, that is, the reverses,

00:34:12.020 --> 00:34:16.410
the rather prominent and discouraging one
of having his 'hostelrie' burned down without

00:34:16.410 --> 00:34:19.540
the mitigating circumstance of any insurance
upon it.

00:34:19.540 --> 00:34:24.740
"I professed a proper amount of sympathy for
so great a calamity, and ventured to inquire

00:34:24.740 --> 00:34:30.850
whether accident or the torch of the incendiary
had wrought such ruin. 'How?' inquired Rustica.

00:34:30.850 --> 00:34:33.770
'Was it the work of an incendiary?' I repeated."

00:34:33.770 --> 00:34:38.860
"She looked at me with a puzzled air for a
moment, and then, ''No,' said she, slowly

00:34:38.860 --> 00:34:44.200
shaking her head, 'no; someone set fire to
it. I held in by a strong effort; but feeling

00:34:44.200 --> 00:34:49.420
that an explosion was imminent, I rushed madly
away.' "That’s my favorite part where they

00:34:49.420 --> 00:34:54.460
overshoot the punch line by about a sentence
and a half.

00:34:54.460 --> 00:34:55.460
[laughter]

00:34:55.460 --> 00:34:58.730
And this is another one. This is from a little
bit later. "A Criticism of the Theatrical

00:34:58.730 --> 00:35:01.450
Criticism in this Morning’s Paper."

00:35:01.450 --> 00:35:02.450
[laughter]

00:35:02.450 --> 00:35:07.290
"The criticism by Sharpley Harpoon, in this
morning’s Star, of last night’s performance

00:35:07.290 --> 00:35:11.690
of 'Sheets and Pillow-cases,' started off
promisingly. For two paragraphs it seemed

00:35:11.690 --> 00:35:15.160
that originality had at last come into its
own in dramatic criticism.

00:35:15.160 --> 00:35:19.670
“Here, finally, you felt, was a dramatic
critic whose one idea had not been to get

00:35:19.670 --> 00:35:24.500
to bed. Rare knowledge of the theatre was
shown in every one of the first two paragraphs.

00:35:24.500 --> 00:35:29.820
The critic had actually seen the show. The
remaining twenty-six paragraphs were something

00:35:29.820 --> 00:35:30.820
else again.

00:35:30.820 --> 00:35:34.780
“While there was still in fact, stronger
evidence that the critic had seen the show

00:35:34.780 --> 00:35:40.090
he was criticizing, there began to appear,
in the third paragraph, an unmistakable sleepiness.

00:35:40.090 --> 00:35:43.530
The suggestion of 'Sheets and Pillow-cases'
was too much for Mr. Harpoon.

00:35:43.530 --> 00:35:48.830
“His third paragraph was a stifled 'hum-hum-hum';
his fourth paragraph was a frank yawn. And

00:35:48.830 --> 00:35:52.480
at the start of the fifth paragraph it was
perfectly obvious that he had used scissors

00:35:52.480 --> 00:35:56.500
and paste, for the next sixteen paragraphs
were given up entirely to a revelation of

00:35:56.500 --> 00:35:57.500
the plot.

00:35:57.500 --> 00:36:01.000
“Nobody who read those sixteen paragraphs
will care to see the show; they robbed the

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:04.750
story of any interest that it might possibly
have. But, it is safe to say, nobody read

00:36:04.750 --> 00:36:08.950
them, so the sum total of nightly attendances
at 'Sheets and Pillow-cases' will be in no

00:36:08.950 --> 00:36:11.160
way affected by Mr. Harpoon’s criticism.

00:36:11.160 --> 00:36:15.910
“On the whole, the criticism was much too
appreciative, as are all criticisms today.

00:36:15.910 --> 00:36:19.970
When shall we have dramatic critics who will
condemn ninety-five plays out of a hundred?

00:36:19.970 --> 00:36:22.490
It makes little difference which ninety-five.
They all need it."

00:36:22.490 --> 00:36:23.490
[laughter]

00:36:23.490 --> 00:36:26.930
"If dramatic critics will just do that for
a while, until the public again has some confidence

00:36:26.930 --> 00:36:31.350
in their discretion, they may then increase
the number gradually. But even the 'gladdest'

00:36:31.350 --> 00:36:34.560
of critics should not be permitted to appreciate
more than fifteen plays out of a hundred."

00:36:34.560 --> 00:36:40.180
"We should have a criticism censorship to
see to that. As for the last eight paragraphs

00:36:40.180 --> 00:36:41.610
of Mr. Harpoon’s comments, it was clear
that he wrote them standing up, putting on

00:36:41.610 --> 00:36:47.010
his hat and coat all the while. He must have
been half way out of the office before the

00:36:47.010 --> 00:36:48.620
last paragraph was complete."

00:36:48.620 --> 00:36:52.930
"When, oh, when, will our dramatic critics
quit going home before they write their criticisms?

00:36:52.930 --> 00:36:57.820
It almost makes us drowsy to write about Mr.
Harpoon’s criticism of 'Sheets and Pillow-cases.'

00:36:57.820 --> 00:37:01.710
Even we critics of critics must watch ourselves,
or we shall give occasion for the creation

00:37:01.710 --> 00:37:04.220
of a new professional group: critics of critics
of critics."

00:37:04.220 --> 00:37:05.220
[laughter]

00:37:05.220 --> 00:37:09.231
"Is it possible that a person may become too
smart to criticize anything except criticism,

00:37:09.231 --> 00:37:14.170
or criticism of criticism? Perhaps that is
why we have so few first-rate first-hand critics

00:37:14.170 --> 00:37:15.800
today."

00:37:15.800 --> 00:37:17.420
[laughter]

00:37:17.420 --> 00:37:21.190
And then, like I said, all kinds of great
information for you. Here's a Philadelphia

00:37:21.190 --> 00:37:26.890
record almanac with food and drinks for sick
people. Beef tea for the sick. You guys will

00:37:26.890 --> 00:37:28.240
love this recipe. Take careful notes.

00:37:28.240 --> 00:37:32.610
"One pound of lean beef, cut into small pieces."
No problem. Got it. "Put into jar without

00:37:32.610 --> 00:37:38.040
a drop of water." OK, we can do that. "Cover
tightly." Easy. "Set in a pot of cold water."

00:37:38.040 --> 00:37:41.840
We got all that stuff here. "Heat gradually
to a boil—fine, and continue this steadily

00:37:41.840 --> 00:37:46.630
for three or four hours until the meat is
like white rags." That's kinda gross. "And

00:37:46.630 --> 00:37:52.010
the juice is all drawn out. Season with salt
to taste, and when cold, skim. The patient

00:37:52.010 --> 00:37:56.420
will often prefer this ice-cold to hot." Sounds
disgusting.

00:37:56.420 --> 00:37:57.420
[laughter]

00:37:57.420 --> 00:38:01.810
The beef tea is one of those nutritive drinks
you see all the time in the Victorian era.

00:38:01.810 --> 00:38:06.040
This has got so much nutrients in them. This
is like toast water.

00:38:06.040 --> 00:38:07.040
[laughter]

00:38:07.040 --> 00:38:12.201
You want some toast water? Here's how you
make it and this is at home. "Carefully remove

00:38:12.201 --> 00:38:16.070
the crust from a slice of stale bread. Toast
the slice through on both sides, but do not

00:38:16.070 --> 00:38:17.070
burn it.

00:38:17.070 --> 00:38:20.030
“Break the slice into three or four pieces
and put them in a pitcher with a small piece

00:38:20.030 --> 00:38:24.570
of orange or lemon peel. Pour on a pint of
boiling water, cover up with a napkin, and

00:38:24.570 --> 00:38:29.800
when cold, strain off the water for use. It
should be freshly made, especially in warm

00:38:29.800 --> 00:38:34.670
weather." So, it's not toast. It's just water
that toast has been in.

00:38:34.670 --> 00:38:35.670
[laughter]

00:38:35.670 --> 00:38:39.610
But if that's not hardy enough for you, how
about some toast soup? "Take a thin slice

00:38:39.610 --> 00:38:42.630
of stale wheat bread and toast until it is
brown through and through; but be careful

00:38:42.630 --> 00:38:45.960
that you do not burn it." If you burn it,
it ruins the toast soup.

00:38:45.960 --> 00:38:46.960
[laughter]

00:38:46.960 --> 00:38:51.240
"While it is still hot, spread some butter
over it, but no more than will strike into

00:38:51.240 --> 00:38:54.920
the bread without leaving any on the surface.
Now break it into fragments, put the pieces

00:38:54.920 --> 00:38:58.460
into a pitcher, and pour on rather more than
half a pint of boiling water. A little pepper

00:38:58.460 --> 00:39:01.710
and salt improves the taste, so they may be
added."

00:39:01.710 --> 00:39:05.030
"This drink is usually found very acceptable
to sick or delicate persons, and at the same

00:39:05.030 --> 00:39:13.850
time is quite nutritious." So, bachelors.
What else we got? We got some brandy. Nothing

00:39:13.850 --> 00:39:14.870
else, just brandy."

00:39:14.870 --> 00:39:15.870
[laughter]

00:39:15.870 --> 00:39:22.230
"When brandy is ordered for a sick child,
it is meant that a few drops, according to

00:39:22.230 --> 00:39:25.460
the age, should be given in water or some
sweet milk as often as the condition of the

00:39:25.460 --> 00:39:29.941
patient requires it. Unless told to do otherwise,
keep it in reserve for the time of the day

00:39:29.941 --> 00:39:33.270
when the sufferer appears to exhibit signs
of being weaker than usual, and then give

00:39:33.270 --> 00:39:37.090
enough to restore it to its average condition
in health, trying not to get above that."

00:39:37.090 --> 00:39:38.090
[laughter]

00:39:38.090 --> 00:39:44.060
"Usually it is more frequently needed in the
latter part of the day, or quite early in

00:39:44.060 --> 00:39:47.240
the morning, than at other times." Basically,
anytime. Milk punch. Milk punch and beef tea

00:39:47.240 --> 00:39:56.130
were like the Adam and Eve of Victorian medicinal
concoctions. “Pour two tablespoonfuls of

00:39:56.130 --> 00:40:01.920
good brandy into six tablespoonfuls of sweet
milk, and add two teaspoonfuls of ground loaf

00:40:01.920 --> 00:40:02.920
sugar.

00:40:02.920 --> 00:40:04.980
"Grate some nutmeg into it, and the punch
is ready for use." Sounds simple, right? "An

00:40:04.980 --> 00:40:08.730
adult person can take a tablespoonful of this
every two or three hours, but for infants

00:40:08.730 --> 00:40:13.240
or children you must remember that one-fourth
of it is brandy."

00:40:13.240 --> 00:40:14.240
[laughter]

00:40:14.240 --> 00:40:17.720
"Milk-punch is much ordered by physicians
for people who have low fevers and for those

00:40:17.720 --> 00:40:21.730
who are debilitated." Milk punch was so popular
back in the Victorian era. I found as many

00:40:21.730 --> 00:40:27.160
different recipes for milk punch as I found
citations for. This one has the rind of Seville

00:40:27.160 --> 00:40:28.190
oranges and lemons.

00:40:28.190 --> 00:40:34.350
It uses rum. Typically, it's some sort of
citrus zest with rum or brandy in with some

00:40:34.350 --> 00:40:39.050
sweet milk or cream. It's really good, right?
Mr. Countryhouse takes a milk punch.

00:40:39.050 --> 00:40:40.050
[laughter]

00:40:40.050 --> 00:40:46.010
I told you how they loved puns, right? So,
essentially, any term that exists in the culture

00:40:46.010 --> 00:40:51.800
is liable for a treatment like this. This
is my favorite image, maybe in the world.

00:40:51.800 --> 00:40:52.800
[laughter]

00:40:52.800 --> 00:40:56.600
When I first found it, I had no idea what
milk punch was.

00:40:56.600 --> 00:40:57.600
[laughter]

00:40:57.600 --> 00:41:03.380
I thought, "All right. It's a milk punch.
Look at that guy."

00:41:03.380 --> 00:41:04.380
[laughter]

00:41:04.380 --> 00:41:11.110
So I thought, "Man, I guess that's what it's
called when a cow kicks you in the gut." That's

00:41:11.110 --> 00:41:12.110
a milk punch. All right.

00:41:12.110 --> 00:41:13.110
[laughter]

00:41:13.110 --> 00:41:15.820
I love this so much, I had to go learn about
milk punch. Now, it's a little less special

00:41:15.820 --> 00:41:22.360
for me. But still, it holds a special place
in my heart. And here's an ad for Chesterfield

00:41:22.360 --> 00:41:29.560
cigarettes. "How I Saved a Policeman's life."
And it's a little poem if I can read it.

00:41:29.560 --> 00:41:31.480
[David Malki clears throat]

00:41:31.480 --> 00:41:35.151
"Even the eggs were tired that morning
and the coffee didn't fool me one bit.

00:41:35.151 --> 00:41:38.080
But when after breakfast my cigarette tasted
awful.

00:41:38.080 --> 00:41:42.340
It was too much and a grouch started.
And walking to work, I swore off smoking

00:41:42.340 --> 00:41:47.550
And decided to fire my office boy.
But just before I decided to kill a policeman,

00:41:47.550 --> 00:41:52.550
A man passed me smoking a cigarette.
I must say, the smoke that drifted back did

00:41:52.550 --> 00:41:54.930
smell good.
I followed him into a store.

00:41:54.930 --> 00:41:58.540
He threw down two dimes and said, 'The same.'
And so did I.

00:41:58.540 --> 00:42:01.680
So, I'm still smoking and still keep that
office boy

00:42:01.680 --> 00:42:10.310
And let that handsome policeman live.
And--"

00:42:10.310 --> 00:42:13.420
It's really very small. Yeah.

00:42:13.420 --> 00:42:18.910
"That man I followed
I'm going to essentially nominate.

00:42:18.910 --> 00:42:24.840
That man I followed for President or something.
For really, those cigarettes do satisfy."

00:42:24.840 --> 00:42:28.210
I like that he was about to kill a policeman.

00:42:28.210 --> 00:42:29.230
[laughter]

00:42:29.230 --> 00:42:34.160
And this is how you sell cigarettes. I did
that in an Obama voice because I could figure

00:42:34.160 --> 00:42:39.761
in like, it's got his cadence to it. "It was
too much. I swore off smoking, so I decided

00:42:39.761 --> 00:42:46.640
to fire my office boy." But not kill a policeman.
You could probably not run this ad today.

00:42:46.640 --> 00:42:47.640
[laughter]

00:42:47.640 --> 00:42:52.340
So, milk punch is my favorite image. "A Bad
Boy's First Reader" is my favorite book ever.

00:42:52.340 --> 00:42:58.840
Frank Bellew, a character cartoonist. This
is a book for children. So, Victorian children's

00:42:58.840 --> 00:43:03.680
literature had one thing in common, it tells
children to sit down and shut up and not doing

00:43:03.680 --> 00:43:04.680
anything of interest at all.

00:43:04.680 --> 00:43:09.300
And stay out of their parent's way. That's
