00:55:00.210 --> 00:55:04.340
This essay by Oliver Wendell Holmes.

00:55:04.340 --> 00:55:10.450
"Our brains are seventy-year clocks. The Angel
of Life winds them up once for all, then closes

00:55:10.450 --> 00:55:15.340
the case, and gives the key into the hand
of the Angel of the Resurrection. Tictac!

00:55:15.340 --> 00:55:19.790
tic-tac! go the wheels of thought; our will
cannot stop them ; they cannot stop themselves

00:55:19.790 --> 00:55:25.040
; sleep cannot still them; madness only makes
them go faster; death alone can break into

00:55:25.040 --> 00:55:29.750
the case, and seizing the ever-swinging pendulum,
which we call the heart, silence at last the

00:55:29.750 --> 00:55:34.500
clicking of the terrible escapement we have
carried so long beneath our wrinkled foreheads.

00:55:34.500 --> 00:55:39.490
"If we could only get at them, as we lie on
our pillows and count the dead beats of thought

00:55:39.490 --> 00:55:43.080
after thought and image after image jarring
through the over-tired organ. Will nobody

00:55:43.080 --> 00:55:47.051
block those wheels, uncouple that pinion,
cut the string that holds these weights, blow

00:55:47.051 --> 00:55:49.290
up the infernal machine with gunpowder?"

00:55:49.290 --> 00:55:55.130
"What a passion comes over us sometimes for
silence and rest, that this dreadful mechanism,

00:55:55.130 --> 00:56:00.240
unwinding the endless tapestry of time, embroidered
with spectral figures of life and death, could

00:56:00.240 --> 00:56:01.970
have but one brief holiday."

00:56:01.970 --> 00:56:07.470
