00:59:21.630 --> 00:59:27.370
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #5: So, how do you
find all of these cool things? I mean, earlier

00:59:27.370 --> 00:59:29.930
you said some people send, like send you right
these books.

00:59:29.930 --> 00:59:36.610
&gt;&gt;David Malki: Yeah. Well, with the way it
started was I think I had one book of clipart

00:59:36.610 --> 00:59:41.170
that was commercially done with clipart. And
then I realized that I was making comics using

00:59:41.170 --> 00:59:45.480
these little engravings. And I'm like, "Well,
I could use this clipart, but everyone else

00:59:45.480 --> 00:59:46.660
has access to the same book of cliparts."

00:59:46.660 --> 00:59:50.830
And so, you see the same images cropping up
a lot. So I thought, "Where did the clipart

00:59:50.830 --> 00:59:55.430
come from?" And so, luckily the books have
introductions and they say this is from such

00:59:55.430 --> 01:00:00.550
and such magazine. So, I went to the library
in LA and they have a bunch of archives on

01:00:00.550 --> 01:00:01.550
microfilm.

01:00:01.550 --> 01:00:06.180
And I was able to look up those particular
magazines and newspapers that they had cited

01:00:06.180 --> 01:00:11.510
and I thought--. Pretty soon, I had a list
of really cool images on this microfilm. I'd

01:00:11.510 --> 01:00:16.620
write down like, such and such year and such
and such title. And then I started looking

01:00:16.620 --> 01:00:20.170
for those exact books on eBay.

01:00:20.170 --> 01:00:24.780
And I'd get ones that were damaged and didn't
have any collector's value because the cover

01:00:24.780 --> 01:00:29.250
was missing or it got stained or something
or a kid had drawn over half of it. So, get

01:00:29.250 --> 01:00:34.480
a sense of the era and the types of titles
that might have things that I'd like. And

01:00:34.480 --> 01:00:35.920
the collection grew over time.

01:00:35.920 --> 01:00:39.710
And then it got to the point where people
would start sending me the things after I'd

01:00:39.710 --> 01:00:47.500
been doing it for a while. And I would look
online for, "Oh, here's Harper's 1879." But

01:00:47.500 --> 01:00:51.890
this article is a two-parter. So, what about
Harper's 1880? What about that one? So, that's

01:00:51.890 --> 01:00:53.960
where Google Books eventually was super helpful.

01:00:53.960 --> 01:00:57.330
And a lot of these articles that--. I mean,
you saw some of them were scans from physical

01:00:57.330 --> 01:01:02.020
paper, but a lot of them were from Google
Books as well because I can do research where

01:01:02.020 --> 01:01:07.560
I can type in a certain author, like looking
up Hiram Maxim. I can see different articles

01:01:07.560 --> 01:01:08.580
published about him.

01:01:08.580 --> 01:01:17.730
And so that's where, at this point, Google
Books has been my whole second library that

01:01:17.730 --> 01:01:28.170
I use for compiling extensive information
like this. Although, I can't use it to make

01:01:28.170 --> 01:01:29.170
the comics because it's all low-res. So, until
next week.

01:01:29.170 --> 01:01:30.290
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #6: How much time do
you spend just paging through actual old books

01:01:30.290 --> 01:01:31.290
or magazines?

01:01:31.290 --> 01:01:37.370
&gt;&gt;David Malki: Umm. A lot. It's tough because
I get really captivated by it. Like, I get

01:01:37.370 --> 01:01:43.300
started--. It's hard. You get just into the
reading and it's hard to stop. And in fact,

01:01:43.300 --> 01:01:47.750
some of the books I got more recently, have
been other languages which makes it way easier

01:01:47.750 --> 01:01:50.910
because I don't get sucked into it.

01:01:50.910 --> 01:01:58.000
But when I'm making the comics, occasionally
I will have an idea for a certain figure or

01:01:58.000 --> 01:02:02.210
character or pose, and then I have to find
something that matches that. And so that's

01:02:02.210 --> 01:02:06.970
a matter of looking through everything with
an eye for, "I need a doctor. I need something

01:02:06.970 --> 01:02:08.730
that looks really like a doctor. Nope, not
here."

01:02:08.730 --> 01:02:10.310
All right. And if I was just drawing the thing,
I could just draw it.

01:02:10.310 --> 01:02:11.310
[laughter]

01:02:11.310 --> 01:02:15.300
But it's--. So sometimes it's, I have a lot
of fun with that. And other times it's dangerous.

01:02:15.300 --> 01:02:17.180
It's dangerous when it gets like that. Yeah.

01:02:17.180 --> 01:02:29.960
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #7: The book, what
was it, the book for bad boys. Do you have

01:02:29.960 --> 01:02:35.230
an impression of how that was received at
the time? Have you seen reviews of it or anything?

01:02:35.230 --> 01:02:37.510
Is that like this?

01:02:37.510 --> 01:02:38.510
[laughter]

01:02:38.510 --> 01:02:44.370
&gt;&gt;David Malki: I wish I knew more about it.
I've seen other people excited nowadays because

01:02:44.370 --> 01:02:50.861
they've discovered it. But I don't think it
was tremendously widely published. Like, there

01:02:50.861 --> 01:02:53.440
are very few copies of it in print still.
Like, left in libraries I've discovered.

01:02:53.440 --> 01:02:58.510
Although what I'm gonna do, I'm gonna be in
DC in a couple months. I'm gonna go to the

01:02:58.510 --> 01:03:03.340
Library of Congress and if they have one,
I'm gonna scan it. And I'm gonna reprint it

01:03:03.340 --> 01:03:04.500
because it's freaking awesome.

01:03:04.500 --> 01:03:05.500
[laughter]

01:03:05.500 --> 01:03:10.450
But Frank Bellew, who again, he was a humorist.
He was a characterist. He was an editorial

01:03:10.450 --> 01:03:16.810
cartoonist. So, I get the sense that it was
written satirically. But there are other pages,

01:03:16.810 --> 01:03:21.730
like I skipped over a bunch of them, but there
are others that are written much more straight

01:03:21.730 --> 01:03:23.810
like a children's book.

01:03:23.810 --> 01:03:30.000
And so, either his humor was not that good
and it was not that clever, so it seems like

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:36.190
you know, "I don't get the joke," or he was
towing that line between, "Yeah, this is plausibly

01:03:36.190 --> 01:03:39.840
a children's book, but I'm gonna slip in this
super weird stuff."

01:03:39.840 --> 01:03:40.840
[laughter]

01:03:40.840 --> 01:03:41.840
Yeah.

01:03:41.840 --> 01:03:47.270
&gt;&gt;MALE AUDIENCE MEMBER #8: You said there
were historical objections to the writing.

01:03:47.270 --> 01:03:53.080
&gt;&gt;David Malki: Yeah. Well, Socrates, whom
we only know because Plato wrote down his

01:03:53.080 --> 01:04:02.460
arguments, objected to writing as a discipline.
He thought that when you wrote something down,

01:04:02.460 --> 01:04:07.320
you weakened your mind because the only way
you can have a legitimate thought is by arguing

01:04:07.320 --> 01:04:08.880
it out with somebody.

01:04:08.880 --> 01:04:14.000
And when you have something written down,
it's only a one-sided argument. So, if you

01:04:14.000 --> 01:04:18.540
read something, you're not being taught it.
You're simply being told it. You don't have

01:04:18.540 --> 01:04:22.880
to puzzle it out with a conversation, like
with Socrates himself.

01:04:22.880 --> 01:04:27.110
And when you write something, you are necessarily
presenting something in a lesser form than

01:04:27.110 --> 01:04:32.400
you might be able to do by explaining it to
somebody and getting their feedback and tailoring

01:04:32.400 --> 01:04:41.730
what you can teach them in a very particular
way. And I don't know that he ever quite sees

01:04:41.730 --> 01:04:43.950
the import that like--.

01:04:43.950 --> 01:04:50.410
There is nothing that persists from generation
to generation unless you write something down.

01:04:50.410 --> 01:04:53.300
And that's where the irony comes in. We wouldn't
even know he objected to writing if Plato

01:04:53.300 --> 01:04:54.610
hadn't written it down.

01:04:54.610 --> 01:04:59.580
And in the same way, there was a monk who
wrote a screed called "In Defense of Scribes"

01:04:59.580 --> 01:05:05.910
about how the printing press was going to
degrade people's understanding of scripture

01:05:05.910 --> 01:05:10.000
because in order to really understand scripture,
you really have to spend hours transcribing

01:05:10.000 --> 01:05:11.000
it.

01:05:11.000 --> 01:05:15.100
And you really get into it. And if you just
are reading a printed version of it, it just

01:05:15.100 --> 01:05:20.280
glosses past you. And of course, nobody would've
known his argument if it hadn't been printed.

01:05:20.280 --> 01:05:21.280
[laughter]

01:05:21.280 --> 01:05:22.280
And circulated. Yeah.

